Based on the patient profile - a 38-year-old woman with moderate to severe ulcerative colitis and a history of pulmonary tuberculosis treated 2 years ago - the top two choices of biological drugs could be Vedolizumab and Ustekinumab.

Vedolizumab specifically targets the gut, reducing systemic side effects, and it is less likely to reactivate latent tuberculosis compared to anti-TNF agents. However, it may be less effective than anti-TNF agents in achieving remission.

Ustekinumab targets interleukin (IL)-12 and IL-23, reducing inflammation in the gut. It is not associated with a high risk of tuberculosis reactivation. However, it is generally used as a second-line therapy and may be less effective in patients who have failed anti-TNF therapy.

